Author: @IllusionQueen4Eva
Comment: Wish there were more games like this, but longer. Much longer. I want games where you can run around as an animal or animal-like being, with at least 20 hours of gameplay and plenty of content to last for days and days. The only game that I know of that does this well is Okami. Outside of the stories and the battles, there are also a bunch of side stuff and minigames and achievements. There's so much to see, so much to do. I found myself having so much fun running around with a rabbit in my mouth and headbutting cows into the lake. There's just so many random things that you can do in the game. Even if you're not a completionist, the game is still 30+ hours long. When I first saw the trailer for Stray, I thought about getting it, but when I found out that the game isn't even ten hours long (I think it can be beaten in two hours), I quickly changed my mind. I wonder if I'll ever see another game like Okami in my lifetime...

Comment:
Maybe others have considered this as I'm only now watching this video,  having the time to do so, but for the language, I'm wondering if that's how cats perceive our language, or at the very least, the language for whatever country this takes place in. So when we see actual English, it's a translation from human language to cat language for our furry friend to understand and follow said instructions. Not 100% certain if that is the case since some of the signs have English shaped letters unless by chance, was in the shape similar to cat language and with some electrical manipulation, made it read what we needed to see.

And Seans' commentary about BB makes me laugh because I have cats that would likely act the same way. Munchkin is terrified of a lot of things, even running away from me still despite wanting cuddles from me. If she was in this environment, she would have a mental breakdown and not likely survive long because of her timid nature. Then again, when cornered, she will fight hard as I've learned when trying to collect her for vet appointments or attempts to treat her for fleas. So she could hold her own likely against those bacterial creatures before she's overwhelmed. However, I can't say how well she'd do hunting wise. Now my other cat, Lester, on the other hand would be absolutely terrified and may likely have a mental and emotional breakdown. Lester is a big baby and is a coward similar to Munchkin. He adores my company and will whine and fuss when I have to leave for work and come running when I come home, begging to be held and cuddled because he missed me so much. In that environment, he would be crying nonstop looking for me, he would be scared, he probably would have no clue how to find food, and if those creatures attacked him, he would have no way to really fight back because he's never had to fight. Lester would not last 5 minutes in that world. Munchkin probably not last more than a couple of days.

Thankfully, they are here at home with me where they are safe with plenty of food, a warm bed to snuggle in, toys to play with, treats to eat, and get as many hugs and kisses from me and give in return to each other and to me.



Adding:

Lester and Munchkin aren't stupid cats. They are quite intelligent in fact. They are just cowardly babies, Munchkin more so, and Lester is more a dramatic crybaby.


Also, the language thing just occurred to me that it's not so much "human" language but could be more likely robotic language they designed for themselves. Could be wrong, or could be half right.

Comment:
This entire review is very biased. And overly critical and stupidly unfair. Acknowledge the glitches, though they were not that common when I played it. Depends on the plateform. In case you didn't know, almost every cat move was captured through motion capture *on real cats*... That's hard work. First evey game to do that for a cat protagonist. Be thankful and pay tribute to the effort. This is almost disrespectful.

Second, the "lack of story through lame band-aid to cover  for missing contend compared to other games that tell the story through visuals blablabla".  Well, what an opinionated statement. The whold industry of video games is dedicated to hate text because, what? People are lazy? They can't read a few (I insist, few) lines? It's perfectly fine to me. You can't just magically include origin stories like that of B12, the small robot, into gameplay or visuals.

Third, the lack of easter eggs. You couldn't be further from the truth. There are plenty of them, signs, old food crates, text (I remember one "Le bout du monde" - bar - entr√©e interdite aux robots" translating into "Edge of the world - bar - only humans allowed", bc the developers are French, etc). You didn't look enough.

Author: @Epicface48
Comment:
I have to say, there's something familiar about this game. It feels like I've been through something like this before.
Whenever I thought about the main points, it just felt nostalgic somehow.
I mean... Consider this, it's a game which has:
-A being not of this world being forced into it to bring back whatever hope remains.
-A soundtrack that encourages exploration and curiosity by staying in the background.
-The reliance on the game's story and plenty of details, characters and dialogue that show how bad and utterly screwed the situation is.
-The quest being complete by shining a bright light on everything.

Sure the gameplay and visuals are drastically different, but this really reminds me of "One Shot," a top-down RPG-maker game where you had to guide a child through a world on the brink of ruin so that they could install the Sun and help re-kindle the people's belief. Both games even have a cat motif and made use of robots to further the story along.
It really makes me wonder if there was any inspiration taken from it...

Author: @4r4ujo86
Comment: Absolutely MAGICAL experience! I could NOT hold back tears at the end, but not in a definitively sad way. It was a mixture of sadness, fullfilment, nostalgia, hope, and sense of wonder. It's difficult for ANY game to elicit these feelings with their story, let alone barely scratching the 5hr mark. Stray's developers know what story they're trying to tell and they don't take or add anything from it. Every environment, every NPC you meet, every word you read feels well-placed and together, they pull you into this world and nudge you to care for its inhabitants, the collective fate they've endured and the hope they cling to so dearly for a better future. This is a MUST PLAY, even if you are not a fan of cats like Skill Up. Try it, you won't be disappointed.

Author: @LHITShappy
Comment: I completed the whole game on a desktop rtx 3080, overall I found that the game is fairly light on both gpu & cpu for the most part, I was getting 80+ to 100fps on average at 4k max on my system depending on scenes. However, if you run the game in dx12 instead of dx11, then the game becomes very demanding on the gpu, barely keeping above 60fps max at 1080p on a rtx 3080, the reason? well after some testing on my part,  it seems that the game uses ray-tracing for AO and most reflections when running in dx12, and the ps5 uses medium settings for shadows and effects at dynamic 4k with no ray-tracing, and my rtx 3080 was getting around 100-120fps avg at 4K in most scenes using ps5 settings. So UE shader compilation stutters aside, a rtx 3060ti/2080s should be enough to match or exceed the ps5 in this title. The fact that you're having performance issues on a rtx 2080ti at 1440p imply that you're probably running the game in dx12.

Author: @shortkingmoon
Comment: vitamin B-12 helps regulate a lot of stuff in your body, including your sleep and mood, and being stuck in dark environments without access to proper nutrition (mainly meat and dairy, like cheese) can lead to B-12 deficiency, which can cause insomnia, body fatigue, brain fog, anxiety, and depression. It can actually get pretty serious and can be hard to fix if your body gets too depleted (one of the worst periods of my life was when i was chronically B-12 deficient, it was absolutely awful). i imagine any humans stuck in the slums would end up suffering from that deficiency, so i sort of like that our little companion is named after this vitamin that does so much to help our bodies thrive and be healthy. it's like we're bringing back good health and good brain vibes to the world, along with trying to open up the city and get Outside again where everyone can hopefully live better lives.

Author: @thefuppits
Comment:
There's two kinds of cat licks no one really mentions. One lick, is the rough kind, designed to scrape food off bones. Yeh, that one can leave you raw. BUT THEN....

Then there's the silky tongue lick, I call it the love lick. Cats can choose how rough they make their tongue, they have control there. Our cats absolutely know the difference.

Sometimes, they rough lick, just because, they're cats and cleaning you and all that. Then, the soft love lick, that is gentle and often accompanied by the hanger tail and some head butting.

Cats are wonderful. This game is wonderful. It is, overall, our favorite game! It is understated, yet rich with character and warmth. It's a collection of butterfly moments, all special, worthy, and beautiful.
